No small amount ol criticism has been passed upon the grouping together in one department ol a legal system ol the topics which are comprised under the ius quod ad res pertinet, and which, we may truly say, would not be co-ordinated upon any other principle of classification. The most solid objection is the inclusion of the law ol Inheritance and that ol obligations in the same division with that ol property and other real rights. The place os the first is due to its character as one of the modes of universal successim, among which it ranke with adrogation, bonorum addictio libertatis causa, and (ln Gaius) conventio in manum, hereditatis in iure cessio, and venditio bonorum. Through this false idea ol proportion the importance of Testamentary and Intestate successim, as an independent branch ol law, is altogether obscured: rnoreover, as Savigny has remarked, these modes ‘quibus res per universitatem adquiruntur' are ex· clusively regarded as titles to rights, whereas they are equally sources of obligations. Accordingly, the German jurists, in their systematic treatises on Roman law, here abandon the Roman classification, and make Inheritance one ol their main divisione, instead ol subordinating it to that between titles to res singulae, and titles to universitates.
